Galkovsky was talking about how when the Americans came to Iceland they built roads, service stations, infrastructure, etc. for the local population. When the British had come they had built a few military installations and the poorest Icelanders tried to live in an empty hangar.

When the Americans occupy you, you get highways, stadiums, football fields, airfields, etc. When the British occupy you, you get some abandoned industrial technical megastructures and a junkyard where drunk and demoralized people roam searching for food or shelter among the junk.

No one understands what the USSR in the 1920s looked like. People think they do, but actually they do not. Terra incognita. The stuff you could see in the 20s USSR was already forgotten by the end of the 30s and even seemed impossible. It was a fever dream decade for the nation.

Esoteric Sinophobia of the night, but Maoist China used to be called "The Empire of Blue Ants" in the USSR due to the Chinese communist uniform being blue. Only thing Google pulls in English is a single result of a newspaper from 1966.

You can actually find plenty of mentions for "blue ants" in the context of China though. Apparently a journalist in Hungary of all possible places came up with it. Which was fucking racist and unacceptable... Offends the dignity of the working Chinese people... Horrible...
